<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Letters to the Editor: Importance of 'positivity' in
confronting cancer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr REX WINSBURY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, As someone recently diagnosed as having terminal cancer, I am pleased
that the articles on cancer by Clive Cookson (Technology: 'Closing in on a
serial killer', November 29 - first in series) will deal with diet, food
supplements and alternative remedies - with some sympathy, I hope, since
they are often (as in my case) ignored by conventional medicine as unproven
or cranky.
Since being written off by the National Health Service, I have met many
people who, by various combinations of radically altered diet, radically
altered life-style and personal determination, appear to have fought off
'the crab'. For how long, of course, who can say? Perhaps I shall find out.
But some doctors attest to the fact that those who attain that
hard-to-define but all-important 'positivity' last longer. That should be
part of the scientific evidence - and 'positivity', unlike certain drugs,
has no nasty side-effects.
Rex Winsbury,
Flat 3, 45 Montpelier Grove,
London NW5 2XG
