<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BY JEFFREY BROWN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures came down with a bump, unwinding much of the recent
rally in another session of relatively thin volume, writes Jeffrey Brown.
The FT-SE 100 December contract stood at 3,041 at the official close, down
52 points. The premium to the cash market was less than two points, or about
half fair value.
Turnover was the same as on Wednesday at 12,828 contracts, so the volume of
selling was not heavy but dealers said sentiment was at times distinctly
negative.
The absence of volume drive was reflected in a wide 48-point trading arc,
with the day's low of 3,036 comparing with the session's peak of 3,086
touched during the early morning.
In late screen-based trading the market took its cue from midsession
weakness on Wall Street, pushing the December contract down to 3,036, with
trading volume rising to in excess of 14,000 lots.
Traded options were active, with turnover reaching 32,365 contracts, against
27,102 on Wednesday, with the bias on the upside and calls outstripping puts
by more than 1,000 lots. FT-SE option trading was 20,557 but with the Euro
FT-SE barely dealt.
HSBC was by far the most active individual stock option with 3,073 lots
transacted. Land Securities and National Power both topped 1,000 contracts
traded.
</TEXT>
