<DATE>941202
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Further signs of growth
depress Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices fell sharply as interest rate fears resurfaced in the wake
of a week-long barrage of strong economic figures, writes Lisa Bransten in
New York.
Late in the afternoon the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped to show a
48-point loss before picking up to end 38.36 down on the day at 3,700.87.
The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 4.77 at 448.92, the American SE composite
fell 2.67 to 431.19 and the Nasdaq composite tumbled 9.12 to 740.61. NYSE
volume was 286m shares.
The National Association of Purchasing Managers reported its index of
economic activity for November at 61.2 per cent, the highest level in more
than 10 years. Several other pieces of economic data released yesterday
added to inflation worries. Personal income in October jumped to 1.4 per
cent from 0.6 per cent in September. That was the largest increase in income
since February. Construction spending also rose beyond economists'
expectations, growing 0.9 per cent in October.
Those numbers just added to concern created by a number of indicators out
earlier in the week. Among the most important were an upward revision of
third-quarter gross domestic product and a leap in consumer confidence.
Mr David Shulman, chief equities strategist at securities house Salomon
Brothers, attributed the markets' decline to fears that the Federal Reserve
would tighten monetary policy again. Investors will now place even more
importance on key employment reports due out today, he said.
So far this year the Fed has raised interest rates six times. Ultimately,
the rising rates will erode corporate earnings by deterring borrowing.
The Nasdaq, where high-technology issues make up approximately 10 per cent
of the market capitalisation, was pulled down further than the other indices
by continued market worries about a possible flaw in the Pentium computer
chip designed by Intel. The Nasdaq composite fell 1.2 per cent, compared
with a 1.0 per cent decrease in the Dow.
Dell Computer shed Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 39 3/4 and Gateway 2000 was down
Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 20 1/4 after securities house CS First Boston
lowered its ratings as both companies prepared to deal with consumer
concerns about the Intel chip in some computers. Intel, which also trades on
the Nasdaq, dipped Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 62 5/8 .
Several NYSE-traded high- technology companies also declined. IBM fell
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 69 5/8 , Digital Equipment was down Dollars 2 3/8
at Dollars 31 5/8 and Compaq Computer receded Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 38
1/4. Hewlett-Packard lost Dollars 3 at Dollars 95 on news that it would
reduce the price of several of its desktop computers.
Chrysler gained ground early in the day after announcing that it would
increase its quarterly dividend by 60 per cent to 40 cents, but was off
Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 47 3/4 by the close. The company's largest
shareholder has been pushing for such a move.
The nation's two largest publicly traded health maintenance organisations
fell after a negative report on a low cost health provider, Kaiser
Permanente, which is not publicly traded. US Healthcare lost Dollars  5/8 at
Dollars 44 1/8 and United Healthcare fell Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 47.
Canada
Toronto drifted lower in cautious trading amid continu-ing worries about
interest rates and as financial markets awaited today's key US employment
data.
The TSE 300 index closed 11.01 easier at 4,082.40 and falls outpaced rises
by 444 to 254 after volume of 70m shares. Eleven of the 14 sub-group indices
were down, led by communication, real estate, pipeline and conglomerate
stocks. Brazil
Equities in Sao Paulo retreated from the day's peaks to finish a net 0.08
per cent off in moderate trade after prices tested some resistance barriers
but did not find support at higher levels.
Brokers said the afternoon's slide was not related to reports saying that
president-elect Fernando Henrique Cardoso had not confirmed that he had
chosen Pedro Malan, of the central bank, as Brazil's new economy minister.
The Bovespa index, up 2.7 per cent initially, lost 37 points on balance at
46,523. Turnover came to RDollars 261.1m (Dollars 305.4m.
News that the National Development Bank has raised RDollars 33.2m through a
successful sale of Banco do Brasil and Petrobras shares helped early
sentiment.
</TEXT>
