FT  02 DEC 94 / International Company News: Borden to discuss rival suitor's
plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Borden, the troubled US food group that has agreed to a Dollars 2bn takeover
by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, the Wall Street investment firm, yesterday
agreed to discuss an offer from a rival suitor, Mr Paul Kazarian.
The company said it would meet Mr Kazarian on Sunday to hear more about his
plan to arrange a restructuring of Borden that would involve buying back 30
per cent of its stock at Dollars 17 a share. That figure represents a
significant premium to the KKR offer of Dollars 14.25 a share.
Borden, however, said Mr Kazarian's proposal was 'silent' on many important
details, and Wall Street expressed its scepticism about the plan by marking
Borden's shares down Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 13 3/4 .
Mr Kazarian, a former chairman and chief executive of the Sunbeam-Oster
consumer products group, runs a Rhode Island investment firm called Japonica
Partners. He has been trying to present himself as a white knight for
Borden.
In his latest letter to Mr Frank Tasco, Borden's chairman, Mr Kazarian has
offered to help finance a Dollars 430m share buy-back by the company, and
has also suggested spinning off its dairy and packaged food businesses.
However, Borden yesterday appeared to pour cold water on the plan, pointing
to a number of potential weaknesses.
</TEXT>
