FT  02 DEC 94 / International Company News: Litton ahead despite sales fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A big cut in interest charges helped Litton Industries, the US defence
group, report a 24 per cent increase in net earnings to Dollars 32.1m from
continuing operations for its first quarter to October.
In the comparable quarter Litton made Dollars 25.9m after tax excluding the
contribution from its non-defence businesses, which were spun off to
shareholders earlier this year.
Earnings per share from continuing operations rose from 55 cents to 68
cents.
Litton has a substantial defence electronics business and builds warships.
But like other defence contractors, it has been suffering the effects of the
global downturn in defence spending.
Sales declined by 6 per cent to Dollars 788m, and although the company
achieved an improvement in operating margins in its advanced electronics
business, total operating profits declined from Dollars 69.6m to Dollars
68.4m.
Net interest paid fell from Dollars 9.6m to Dollars 1.3m, resulting from the
early extinguishment of high-cost debt in July.
Mr John Leonis, chief executive, said Litton's financial position remained
strong, and that the company planned to invest in acquisitions related to
its aerospace and defence businesses as the fiscal year progressed.
