<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Hanson shops around after rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hanson shares continued their recent recovery yesterday as the Anglo-US
conglomerate reported a 26 per cent increase in annual operating profits to
Pounds 1.23bn and said it was ready to take on another big acquisition.
The shares have lagged the market this year on worries that the group was
running out of steam. But Lord Hanson, chairman, declared yesterday that its
future 'remains exciting'.
'The economic resurgence has provided a stimulus to improve trading profits
still further, while seeking strategic opportunities to enhance shareholder
value,' he said.
Mr Derek Bonham, chief executive, said the group had excellent opportunities
for organic growth but was also ready to take on another big deal. 'The
balance sheet is in a position to make another major step forward if we find
the opportunity. That is certainly what we are looking for.'
Last year's operating profits, of which 54 per cent (against 43 per cent)
were generated in the US, were boosted by the acquisition of Quantum
Chemical in a Dollars 3.2bn (Pounds 1.95bn) deal in September 1993, which
contributed Pounds 100m after interest. Gearing, which rose to 86 per cent
on completion, has now been reduced to 58 per cent, after Pounds 945m of
disposals.
Including disposal gains, group pre-tax profits rose to Pounds 1.35bn, from
Pounds 1.02bn, on sales of Pounds 11.2bn (Pounds 9.76bn). Excluding
exceptional items, profits were little changed at Pounds 1.01bn (Pounds
992m) and earnings per share, on the same basis, were 14.7p (14.4p). As
previously signalled, the quarterly dividend is 3p (2.85p) for a total of
11.7p (11.4p).
Mr Bonham said that Hanson wanted to combine dividend growth with a gradual
reduction in cover from 1.25 times to about 1.5.
The figures were accompanied by an upbeat assessment of prospects for the
next two years. Mr David Clarke, chief executive of the US arm, Hanson
Industries, said: 'We are very much on a roll, particularly with Quantum. We
are even more enthusiastic about prospects for 1995 despite recent interest
rate hikes.'
Most of Hanson's cyclical chemicals and constructionrelated businesses are
recovering strongly on both sides of the Atlantic, while profits at Peabody,
the largest US coal producer, bounced to Pounds 144m (Pounds 70m) following
the end of the long and expensive strike.
The improvement in operating profit was largely offset by an interest bill
of Pounds 223m (compared with income of Pounds 14m the previous year). This
reflected higher borrowings but also the reduced spread between US and UK
interest rates which Hanson has arbitraged very successfully.
Mr William Landuyt, finance director, warned that the interest bill was
likely to rise again this year.
The shares added 2p to 237p.
Lex, Page 16
Details and Background, Page 19
</TEXT>
