<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Democracy 'threatened by quangos'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The growth of the 'unelected state' - the network of quangos operating on
the fringes of government - represents a direct threat to Britain's
democratic system, says a newly-published report.
The research shows that important decisions about the expenditure of
taxpayers' money are being taken behind closed doors by government
appointees.
It says the accountability of quangos - quasi-autonomous non-governmental
organisations - to parliament is often tenuous, while their accountability
to local communities is negligible. However, they are in charge of about a
fifth of public expenditure.
It adds: 'It is a system wide open to charges of party political influence
and corruption.'
The report, commissioned by the public service union Unison from Durham
University's Department of Sociology and Social Policy, demands that quangos
be reformed.
It proposes a review by government of quangos, the publication of details of
how members are chosen, an annually published register of quangos and board
members including occupation details and remuneration, and the publication
by each quango of a register of members' interests.
Unison also intends to develop a 'Quangowatch' network to monitor quangos
throughout Britain.
Who Runs the North? Regional Secretary, Unison northern regional office,
Southend, Fernwood Rd, Newcastle upon Tyne. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
