<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Railway inspector numbers increased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Health and Safety Executive has increased the number of railway
inspectors to 46 in response to the proposed privatisation of British Rail.
The addition of eight inspectors comes in a year in which the number of
crashes involving passenger trains doubled, although the number of
passengers and staff killed on the railways in 1993-94 was the lowest on
record, the executive's railway inspectorate said in its annual report.
Mr Stanley Robertson, the chief railways inspector said the extra inspectors
were required because companies 'with little or no previous experience of
operating on the railway and managers with limited experience of safety
issues may enter the railway industry as the BR monopoly is broken.
'Unless considerable care is taken, there can be no confidence that risk
will be effectively controlled right from the start and that important
matters will not fall between the safety arrangements of the various
parties.'
New regulations had been introduced and companies involved in railway
operations were required to present 'safety cases' explaining their
procedures. Even so, 'co-operation and safety interaction between operators
will be an important element in safety cases,' the report said.
Railtrack, which has taken over BR's track and stations, has had its safety
case accepted by the inspectorate. But others have not been sufficiently
detailed.
The number of 'significant' train accidents - those potentially the most
dangerous to passengers - increased from 133 to 142 in the year to March.
Passenger deaths fell to 17 from 28 the year before.
HSE Books, PO Box 1999, Sudbury, Suffolk CO10 6FS. Pounds 11.
</TEXT>
