<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Guilty verdicts for 33 in fraud trials: Birmingham mortgage
swindle raised Pounds 35m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
West Midlands police have secured the conviction of 33 people in a series of
cases involving the fraudulent deception of building societies and banks to
obtain Pounds 35m.
Cases against 43 people were heard in a series of trials at the Birmingham
Crown Court. The trials, which were subject to reporting restrictions,
started in January and finished this week.
The court hearings followed some of the most elaborate police investigations
into mortgage fraud in the UK. Police operations, code-named Operation
Trooper, started in November 1990 and involved 23 officers.
'Operation Trooper is certainly the longest and most complex fraud
investigation ever conducted by us,' said Det Supt Tim Salt, head of West
Midlands Fraud Squad.
Police examined the buying and selling of 200 properties and identified 70
in the Sutton Coldfield and Erdington areas of north Birmingham as subject
to mortgage fraud. The transactions took place at the peak of the
residential property market, in and around 1988.
The fraud system worked on the basis of inflating the value of a particular
property. A member of the fraud ring would purchase a property legitimately
with the idea of selling it on to another member of the ring.
Once acquired, the property in question would have its value inflated and,
with the assistance of a spurious valuation, an application would be made
for a mortgage.
The members of the ring covered their tracks by using false names and
addresses on their mortgage applications. Once the mortgage funds were paid,
they disappeared as far as the lender was concerned: the members of the
fraud ring made no repayments.
Funds by this system of fraud were obtained from some of the leading housing
market lenders, including Abbey National, Birmingham Midshires, Bradford &amp;
Bingley, Coventry and Leeds Permanent building societies, the Bank of
Scotland and Barclays, Midland and National Westminster banks.
Their losses, although covered by indemnity policies, go further than the
amounts by which they were defrauded. The properties subject to the
fraudulent mortgages were repossessed, but their values have declined in
line with the downturn of the housing market.
Police explained that the channel to the lenders was through The Mortgage
Shop, Priory Queensway, Birmingham, whose principal was Mr Paul Fewtrell.
The property valuations came from Mr Ian Bain and the conveyancing was done
by Mr Stephen Hyde, a legal executive at Roger Lloyd and Company, a
Birmingham firm of solicitors now defunct.
The ringleader was Mr David William Harris of Monmouth Drive, Sutton
Coldfield. He was sentenced to six years' imprisonment for conspiracy to
defraud. His sentence, the most severe of the penalties given to the 33
guilty, was later reduced to five years.
At the first trial of the series, both Mr Bain and Mr Fewtrell were
acquitted.
However, two members of The Mortgage Shop management, Mr Dean Taylor and Mr
Phillip Kieley, were found guilty and sentenced respectively to 12 months'
imprisonment and 250 hours' community service.
So far 30 of the 33 guilty have received sentences ranging from community
service orders to spells of imprisonment. The remaining three will be
sentenced next month.
Meanwhile, West Midlands Fraud Squad has filed with the Crown Prosecution
Service evidence which may lead to two prosecutions for commercial property
fraud, this time involving trading estates in the Black Country.
</TEXT>
