<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Mawhinney warned of gridlock at London's airports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A powerful group of aviation, business and tourism bodies today urged Mr
Brian Mawhinney, the transport secretary, to increase capacity at airports
in the London area before the region reaches 'gridlock'.
Demand at airports in the south-east will exceed the capacity of existing
and proposed airport development early in the next century, according to a
letter sent to Mr Mawhinney yesterday.
The letter is the most co-ordinated attempt by organisations lobbying for
increased capacity and comes shortly before the government joins the debate
over a recent Department of Transport working group report, Runway Capacity
to Serve the South East (Rucatse).
The letter is from the chairman and other senior executives of the British
Air Transport Association, the Chartered Institute of Transport, the Air
Transport Users Council, the Confederation of British Industry, the British
Chambers of Commerce, the London Chamber of Commerce, the British American
Chamber of Commerce and the Association of British Travel Agents.
It warns that traffic lost to the UK will be to the gain of 'our near
European neighbours,' such as Charles de Gaulle in Paris, or Schipol in
Amsterdam.
The letter counsels the government to assess the economic consequences of
failing to meet future demand, especially the loss of potential inward
investment and tourism revenues.
It says the government should consider alternatives to Rucatse. The Rucatse
report argued that more use could be made of existing airport capacity in
the south-east than had been assumed. Greater use of regional airports would
delay the need for expansion in London.
The options, according to the letter, would include 'complementary
facilities' - which are understood to mean satellite feeder airports close
to Gatwick or Heathrow - and 'close parallel runways', meaning second
runways next to existing ones.
The Bata said figures last month from BAA, the airports operator, showed
passenger numbers up 7 per cent at Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted in the
first nine months of 1994, compared with a year ago.
The association said the figures were higher than earlier BAA and Department
of Transport projections which had suggested that London's airports would be
able to accommodate demand until 2015.
</TEXT>
