<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Pension schemes win concession on bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is preparing to accede to pleas from the UK's largest
occupational pension schemes not to saddle them with a disproportionate
share of financing a new pensions regulator.
It is understood that the forthcoming bill for the reform of occupational
pensions will call for a flat per-member levy across the industry to help
finance a compensation scheme for benefits lost through fraud or
misappropriation.
However, the cost of the new regulator, estimated in a June white paper at
Pounds 10m a year, will be spread differently.
The government is expected to propose a 'weighted' levy which will ease the
contribution required of schemes with the most members.
Department of Social Security officials made clear this week that the main
provisions would be included in a bill that is expected to run to around 140
clauses and be published before the end of the year.
It is expected that the bill will be introduced in the House of Lords,
probably in mid to late December.
'The vast majority of our provisions will be in the bill and everything will
be debatable,' DSS officials said. 'There may be some secondary regulations
but these will not inhibit debate.'
DSS officials say the main provisions of the bill are little changed from
those stipulated in the government's white paper on occupational pensions
which was published this summer.
It is understood that there will be no change in the proposed powers of the
Occupational Pensions Regulator.
However, ministers have been engaged in last-minute consultations with the
industry on a number of important aspects of the bill.
In particular, there has been fierce debate over how a proposed minimum
solvency requirement on pension schemes will be set.
While employers' groups have been lobbying heavily to allow their equity
holdings to count more heavily towards the solvency calculation, actuaries -
the profession that must certify scheme solvency - have resisted. Equities
offer too little certainty of return to be held against liabilities for
pensions currently in payment.
Actuaries have told the government they will only use the looser standard if
a political decision is made by the DSS.
The bill will also clarify some aspects relating to the election of trustees
to pension schemes.
Labour MPs and many parts of the pensions industry have become concerned
that some of the most contentious clauses of the bill will not be contained
in the initial legislation, but will appear in secondary legislation or in
guidance notes issued by the Institute and Faculty of Actuaries.
However, DSS officials have been anxious to stress that public debate will
be held on all aspects of the bill.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
