<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Gridlock fear for London's airports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A group of aviation, business and tourism bodies are urging Mr Brian
Mawhinney, the transport secretary, to increase capacity at airports in the
London area before the region reaches gridlock, Andrew Baxter writes.
Demand at airports in the south-east will exceed the capacity of existing
and proposed airport development early in the next century, says a letter
sent to Mr Mawhinney.
The letter is from the chairman and other senior executives of the British
Air Transport Association, the Chartered Institute of Transport, the Air
Transport Users Council, the Confederation of British Industry, the British
Chambers of Commerce, the London Chamber of Commerce, the British American
Chamber of Commerce and the Association of British Travel Agents.
They warn that traffic lost to the UK would be to the gain of 'our near
European neighbours'.
The options they propose include 'complementary facilities' - which are
understood to mean satellite feeder airports close to Gatwick or Heathrow -
and second runways next to existing ones.
</TEXT>
