<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Companies 'cut cash for Tories'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative party has suffered a big fall in cash gifts from companies,
says a survey published today by the Labour Research Department, a research
organisation funded mainly by unions.
Labour Research could find only 168 companies that had made donations in the
year to March to the Conservative party, the lowest such figure produced by
the research group.
The companies in the survey donated a total of Pounds 2.51m, which is the
third lowest sum reported by the annual survey since 1979.
The total was down substantially from Pounds 7.76m in 1991 - the last
comparable year because gifts for 1992 and 1993 were boosted by the
closeness of the last general election.
The annual survey by Labour Research is considered a good guide to how much
companies are donating to the Conservatives, although it cannot be regarded
as completely authoritative. It covers about 5,000 UK companies and is
thought to capture most of the large donations made by big public companies.
The survey does not include cash donated by individuals or amounts donated
by companies not listed in the UK.
The Pounds 2.51m traced by Labour Research accounts for just over a quarter
of the Pounds 9.37m which was donated to the Conservatives in the year to
the end of March from companies and individuals.
In the past two years several big companies have cut back or stopped
donations either because of reductions in profits during the recession or
because they have not wanted to be seen publicly to be diverting large sums
to the Conservatives.
Among the companies cutting back have been food manufacturer United
Biscuits, construction company Taylor Woodrow, the Argyll supermarket group
and drinks company Allied Domecq.
</TEXT>
