FT  02 DEC 94 / Ministers bullish on VAT vote win
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior ministers were increasingly confident yesterday that the government
would be able to beat off a Labour attempt to force a vote on the second
stage of the imposition of value added tax on heating fuel.
But the vote appears likely to be close after confirmation that the nine
Ulster Unionist MPs, who supported the government in Monday's confidence
vote on Europe, will vote with the opposition.
But Tory whips are hopeful that no more than half of the dozen Tory VAT
rebels will go through with threats to defy the party whip - suggesting that
the government will have a majority of between two and eight votes.
Two Conservative backbenchers announced in the Commons last night that they
would not back the government next week in the vote. Mr Nicholas Winterton,
Conservative MP for Macclesfield, said there was 'little to celebrate in the
Budget'. He added: 'The decision to proceed bull-headed with the imposition
of the second tranche of VAT on domestic fuel bills will be widely
resented.'
Mr Phil Gallie, the Conservative MP for Ayr and another critic of the
decision to impose 17.5 per cent VAT on domestic fuel, said he would abstain
when Labour's procedural motion was put to the vote on Tuesday night.
However, senior ministers think that much of the steam has gone out of the
rebellion since the failure of rightwing attempts to raise sufficient
support for a challenge to Mr John Major's leadership. Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the chancellor, was breezily confident that the government would defeat the
Labour motion.
The motion amounts to a procedural device that would pave the way for a
further vote on the implementation of the second tranche of VAT during the
passage of the finance bill.
</TEXT>
