<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Experts attack insolvency laws
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Urgent reform of the insolvency laws to correct serious injustices was
called for yesterday by Justice, the civil liberties pressure group.
A committee chaired by Mr David Graham QC and including Mrs Justice Arden
and Mr Philip Pink, former deputy inspector-general of the government's
insolvency service, concluded there was 'a serious imbalance' in the system
which operated overwhelmingly to the prejudice of small businesses and
individuals.
The system introduced by the 1986 Insolvency Act produced 'minimal financial
benefits' for unsecured creditors, and a lack of alternative procedures
forced far too many small consumer debtors into bankruptcy. Bankruptcies
have risen from about 4,000 a year at the time of the Cork committee's
review of insolvency law at the end of the 1970s to 40,000 in 1993.
The committee says that if the injustice to ordinary creditors is not
remedied soon it will result in the 'bankruptcy of bankruptcy'.
By contrast the government has done extremely well out of the present
regime. In 1992-93 it earned more than Pounds 50m from holding funds of
insolvent estates, Pounds 9m more than it costs to run the insolvency
service.
Insolvency practitioners and large secured creditors such as banks have also
benefited.
The committee recommends:
The appointment of an insolvency ombudsman. More advice for small debtors
provided by the government and insolvency practitioners on a 'pro bono'
basis.
The creation of a two-tier bankruptcy system to separate serious or
fraudulent cases from ordinary small debtors.
A creditors' charter to ensure creditors' concerns are adequately met by
insolvency practitioners.
Insolvency Law: An Agenda for Reform. Justice, 59 Carter Lane, London EC4.
Pounds 4.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
