<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Blair's school choice starts row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair's political honeymoon as Labour leader ended yesterday in a
blaze of controversy over his decision to send his son to a grant-
maintained school outside local authority control.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, education secretary, said Mr Blair's choice of the
Roman Catholic London Oratory school for his son Euan, 10, marked a U-turn
for Labour.
Mr John Major seized on the issue in the Commons, accusing Mr Blair of using
the grant maintained system while planning 'to remove the same privileges
from everyone else'.
The decision also worried the National Union of Teachers, which said the
school had opted out of centralised salary agreements as well as local
authority financing.
Mr Blair, campaigning in the west Midlands for this month's Dudley
by-election, said he hoped the issue would not be 'a political football to
be kicked across the political divide'.
Mr Blair said he and his wife Cherie had chosen the London Oratory because
it was a Roman Catholic school that regularly took pupils from his son's
present school, the Joan of Arc primary in Islington, London, where the
family lives.
'The Labour party is in favour of choice for people and decent schools for
people,' Mr Blair told BBC television. 'I am not going to make a choice for
my child on the basis of what is the politically correct thing to do.'
Labour officials said there was no conflict between Mr Blair's choice of
school and the party's education policy, which is being reviewed by Mr David
Blunkett, appointed shadow education secretary in a shadow cabinet reshuffle
last month.
Mr Blunkett has dropped plans to force grant maintained schools back into
the local authority system, but remains committed to ending further opt-outs
and to changing the funding system.
Mrs Shephard said there were two local authority-run Roman Catholic
comprehensive schools in Islington which Euan could have attended.
'Mr and Mrs Blair's decision will cause huge embarrassment to his Labour
colleagues, who will face the impossible task of squaring this decision with
the party's words,' she said.
Mr Graham Lane, education committee chairman of the Labour-controlled
Association of Metropolitan Authorities, said Mr Blair's decision was 'not
helpful to the party position'.
Mr Doug McAvoy, NUT general secretary, said Mr and Mrs Blair were
'exercising a choice provided by Conservative legislation few other parents
could contemplate.
'The Oratory School has not only opted out of local authority control - it
is also the only school to have opted out of the statutory arrangements
governing teachers' pay and conditions of service,' he said.
</TEXT>
