<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Customs chief insists job cuts are in the line of duty:
Battlelines drawn up as unions attack the plan to shed 4,000 staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER and RICHARD WOLFFE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Valerie Strachan, chairman of Customs and Excise, has denied union
claims that the shedding of 4,000 jobs over the next five years is driven
solely by the government's need to find scope for tax cuts before the next
election.
She said the plan - attacked by unions as risking increased drug smuggling
and a loss of VAT revenue - 'does not represent for us a fundamental change
in direction. It is a further pretty big step down the road we were already
travelling.'
The Customs and Excise service has already seen changes in recent years, not
least through the opening of European border controls under the single
market. Its 25,000 staff is split between 12,000 doing value added tax work;
9,000 in customs (looking for drugs, firearms and pornography); 2,000 in
excise (responsible for duty collection from brewers and distillers) and
inland customs, and 3,000 support staff.
In the year to March, the service gathered revenue of Pounds 66.7bn - 45 per
cent of the total government tax yield. Nearly 60 per cent of the
department's revenue comes from VAT and only 3 per cent from Customs duties.
Customs officers no longer limit the amount of duty-paid drink and
cigarettes individuals can bring into the country from the rest of Europe -
so long as they are for private consumption. But 240 plain-clothes excise
verification officers monitor pubs and off-licences to check that goods
imported in this way are not being sold on.
The NUCPS and the CPSA, the main civil service unions involved, had been
campaigning for an increase in anti-smuggling staff. They said: 'The
incentive to potential smugglers is all too clear if you consider the
potential profits involved. A single lorry load of smuggled cigarettes would
result in a loss of tax revenue of over Pounds 600,000, most of which would
end up as pure profit to the smuggler.'
The Brewers and Licensed Retailers Association said that, if customs staff
were to be weakened, 'it can only be good news for bootleggers and the
French chancellor'.
Mrs Strachan said that 'adding back' customs staff into intelligence work
would maintain, or even improve, effectiveness. She added: 'We will be
placing a greater emphasis on high-risk and complex work, and give less
priority to routine activity where the risks are lower and results have been
less.'
The unions argue that cutting 550 front-line anti-smuggling officers risks
increased drug smuggling. They point out that two of the UK's biggest drug
hauls - cannabis worth Pounds 35m last month at Felixstowe and Pounds 9m
worth of heroin at Sheerness, Kent, in October  - were the result of routine
checks, not specific intelligence. Mr John Amos, of NUCPS, said: 'Smugglers
aren't idiots - if they see there are gaps, they will exploit them.'
However, police officers welcomed the shift in anti-smuggling work towards
operations against trafficking. Mr Keith Hellawell, the chief constable of
West Yorkshire who chairs the drugs committee of the Association of Chief
Police Officers, said: 'The fight against crime will not be affected by the
changes because our work is already intelligence-led.'
Most attention has focused on the dangers of increased drug smuggling, but
the biggest single group of jobs to go from the department will be 2,000 VAT
officials. Mrs Strachan said a large part of this reduction was due to
'rethinking our approach to VAT control'.
She added: 'Many businesses are either very small or very compliant or
possibly both.' They did not need to be visited as often as they were.
Mr Dave Morris, NUCPS assistant general secretary, said that all businesses
are guaranteed a visit by a Customs inspector within three years of
registering for VAT under the Citizen's Charter. 'We will have to tear up
that commitment - we simply cannot do it with these proposals,' he said.
The department's most recent annual report, for the year to March, admitted
that only 80.5 per cent of newly registered businesses were being visited
within three years.
Mr Ian Hanford, policy chairman for the National Federation of Small
Businesses, said: 'If you are given bad tax advice and it is five or six
years before the VAT officers come in, there could be horrendous penalties
which could wipe the business out.
'Where VAT officers are looked on as protection, fewer inspections could be
bad news.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
