<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Brokers believe in Santa George
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new entry in this week's box office charts is the animated film The
Nightmare before Christmas.
In the movie, Halloween figures take over the role of Santa Claus and ruin
the Yuletide cheer. But in the nightmares of retailers and some stock market
investors, the figure of Christmas terror is personified in the more
down-to-earth form of Mr Eddie George.
Many fear that the governor of the Bank of England will press for a further
rise in base rates when he meets Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, on
December 7. That might deliver a heavy blow to consumers in the
all-important Christmas shopping season.
Mr John Shepperd, chief economist at Yamaichi International bank (Europe),
said: 'A lot of shops do a quarter of their turnover in the run-up to
Christmas. To hit consumers with the psychological shock of a rate rise
would be supremely bad timing.'
The Bank of England has already warned that rates will have to rise at some
point over the next few months if the government is to achieve its aim of
getting underlying inflation within the lower half of its 1 per cent to 4
per cent target range by the end of this parliament.
Mr Adam Cole, UK economist at brokers James Capel, said there was a strong
case for an early rate rise: 'If you look at the Bank's list of inflation
concerns, almost every one has deteriorated. The pace of growth has been
revised up further, and lead indicators such as the CBI survey suggest the
economy is not losing momentum in the fourth quarter.'
However, Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist at Salomon Brothers, the
stockbrockers, noted that October's economic data, such as retail sales and
the M4 measure for broad money supply, had been weak. He thought there had
been insufficient evidence since Mr Clarke and Mr George last met on
November 2 to persuade the two to act.
Certainly Mr Clarke might be able to put a compelling case for delay. This
week's Budget confirmed the previously announced tax rises and imposed
further controls on public spending. Both should be expected to slow
economic growth. Indeed, the Treasury is forecasting that the UK's gross
domestic product, having grown at 4 per cent in 1994, will rise by only 3.25
per cent next year.
Furthermore, in the red book which accompanied the Budget, the Treasury took
an optimistic line on the size of the 'output gap', one of the key measures
used by economists for assessing the scope for inflationary pressure.
'There is almost certainly a sizeable (output) gap,' it said. 'In other
words, there is still spare capacity in the economy as a whole. This should
allow the economy to continue growing faster than trend without any
significant upward pressure upon prices.'
There are also one or two technical details that might make the timing of a
December rate rise difficult. On the day of the meeting, the Bank of England
will hold a gilt auction. Back in January 1993, an interest rate cut held
just before an auction upset many marketmakers.
While a interest rate rise this time might not disrupt the market - gilt
prices might benefit from evidence of the government's anti-inflationary
commitment - the timing would still look awkward. Mr Cole said: 'Were the
auction to go badly and traders end up with a lot of stock, the Bank
wouldn't want to clobber traders with a rate rise as well.'
Another timing problem for the governor is that he is giving evidence on the
Budget to the Commons' Treasury and civil service committee on December 8.
That would mean that, if he received the go-ahead from Mr Clarke to raise
rates, he would have to raise them before he addressed the committee to
avoid prevarication and possible deceit.
On balance, then, analysts think a rate rise will be delayed, if only until
January. Mr Shepperd said: 'Waiting a month until January probably won't
make that much difference to the economy. And Eddie George may find Kenneth
Clarke more receptive.'
When a rise is announced, Mr Cole thinks it will be of half a percentage
point. 'More than half a point would seem like panic, and a quarter of a
point is not enough.'
So even if Mr George does allow retailers to enjoy a merry Christmas, he
could still deny them a happy new year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
