<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Nato's advance grinds to halt on Russian front
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Western and Russian officials often use a catchphrase to describe the
relations they would like to see between Moscow and the Atlantic alliance:
no vetoes, no surprises.
In other words, neither side will claim the right to dictate how the other
should behave, but each will avoid giving the other unpleasant shocks.
Last night, both Russian and Nato officials were accusing one another of
committing precisely that sin.
Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russian foreign minister, came to Brussels for a
set-piece event intended to symbolise a new co-operative relationship
between Moscow and the western alliance which was founded as a counterweight
to the Soviet bloc.
The launch of a military co-operation programme was also envisaged by the
west as part of a 'charm offensive' supposedly to blunt Moscow's
determination to frustrate Nato enlargement.
Both Mr Kozyrev's visit and other aspects of the western blandishments to
Russia had been carefully prepared. But the expectations of a happy and
essentially ceremonial encounter were dashed.
The soft-spoken minister arrived from Paris - where he made a bold proposal
for closer relations between Moscow and the European Union's defence
institutions - in a mood of apparent bonhomie. He recalled jocularly that
Brussels was his birthplace and that Mr Willy Claes, Nato's new
secretary-general, was an old acquaintance.
He then brandished before the television cameras a weighty document, which
Russian and Nato officials had been quietly drafting for months, and which
was intended to map out future links between Moscow and the alliance.
The document details Russia's activities within the Partnership for Peace, a
military co-operation programme which Nato has offered to all its former
enemies. It also spells out a broader Russia-Nato relationship which Moscow
has successfully demanded.
Only after ministers went into closed session did word leak out that Mr
Kozyrev was holding back from depositing his copy of the document at Nato -
and hence refusing to launch the programme.
The reason he gave for this piece of high drama was that Russia objected to
the document agreed a few hours earlier by Nato foreign ministers, which
spells out an accelerated programme for integrating ex-communist countries
into the alliance.
'At first reading this document raises more questions than answers,' Mr
Kozyrev said of the Nato text, adding that he had discussed it with
President Boris Yeltsin. He still hoped the Russia-Nato programme would go
ahead, but the alliance would have to provide some clarifications.
Nato officials said the western reaction was one of 'shock and
disappointment', adding
that they had been at pains to keep Russia informed over the past few weeks
on their ideas for an accelerated enlargement programme.
The Russian gesture confirms what western governments have earnestly wanted
not to believe: Moscow still objects strongly to incorporation of Poland,
Hungary, the Czech Republic and Slovakia into the western defence system, as
long as it is excluded.
Nato has for the past year been engaged in a bizarre sort of mating dance
with its former central European adversaries which desperately yearn for
protection from Russia which is unhappy about seeing its former satellites
engulfed by the western security system.
Hours before Mr Kozyrev's arrival yesterday, western officials were
congratulating themselves on having 'squared' Russian concerns. But it is
now clear that Russia will spring plenty more surprises as it tries to
exercise an effective veto on over-hasty Nato expansion.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
    BEZ  Belgium, EC.
