<HEADLINE>
FT  02 DEC 94 / Council tax bills likely to rise after government cuts
funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday imposed the toughest financial settlement on local
authorities since the 1970s, with a cash cut in the funding they will
receive from central government and a projected rise in council tax bills of
twice the rate of inflation.
Councillors of all parties reacted angrily, predicting job losses, a
reduction in services and larger school class sizes.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, announced that aggregate external
finance for local authorities - from specific grants and business rates -
will be reduced by 0.4 per cent in 1995-96, to Pounds 34.672bn.
He told the Commons the settlement was 'tough' but said it was clear many
authorities had 'considerable scope to increase their efficiency'.
Environment Department officials said the move meant a shift in the tax
burden from centrally raised taxation to the council tax. The government
estimates that councils which meet its standard spending guidelines should
raise bills for properties in the council tax band C - valued at between
Pounds 52,000 and Pounds 68,000 - by about 4.6 per cent next year, from
Pounds 467 to Pounds 491. Under the same measure, Band D (Pounds 68,000 to
Pounds 88,000) bills would rise from Pounds 525 to Pounds 551.
Councils predicted an average rise of 6 per cent.
Strict 'capping' of council budgets by the government is intended to prevent
excessive rises.
Councils outside inner London will have their budgets cut if they spend more
than the government's assessment for them, and if they raise spending by 0.5
per cent or more compared with this year. Inner London councils will be
allowed a 2 per cent rise.
There will also be a cut in the transitional relief paid to authorities
which lost out after the council tax replaced the old community charge or
poll tax. This will lead to additional increases varying from Pounds 67 a
year to Pounds 137, according to which band the property is in, on top of
the so-called standard spending council tax.
In a joint statement, the three English local authority associations said:
'Councils will suffer a very difficult year, and the public - in particular
the elderly, the infirm and children - face losing vital services because
the government will not let local authorities spend enough to give their
communities what they need.'
Several Tory backbenchers also registered concern. Sir Peter Fry, MP for
Wellingborough, protested that Northamptonshire would have a 'very
disappointing' settlement for the second year running, requiring many
teachers to be made redundant.
Mrs Rita Taylor, a Tory district councillor for Bromsgrove and a member of
the Association of District Councils' finance panel, said: 'Conservatives in
local government are not a happy lot. The initial reaction of many will be
despair.'
Councils stretched, Page 8
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
