<DOCNO>FT944-5780</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ELAD8AHYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 94 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1994 (16): Taking a
pragmatic approach - Production information systems / A comprehensive
network back-up system means that Philips Components' factory can work round
the clock without constant technical support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It takes a leisurely two hours or more for a television screen to progress
from a dollop of molten glass through several cooling and cleaning processes
to the finished product at Philips Components.
The company's factory on the edge of Burnley, Lancashire, has therefore
taken a pragmatic view about the frequency of updates and levels of back-up
it needs in its on-line production information system.
The system, developed last year as part of a multi-million pound refit of
the entire plant, provides information which is six minutes old. The
information network depends largely on a single central computer with
various levels of fall-back without expensive duplication of equipment. The
350 staff keep the highly automated factory working round the clock,
producing 2.5m screens a year.
Until the refit and the new system, information was gathered on old Apple
and BBC PCs. Reports were printed once a day and photocopied for
distribution in time for the following day's production meeting. Information
was therefore up to 24 hours old, so by the time problems were analysed from
the printed reports it could be 30 hours after the initial incident before
things were put right.
The importance of these adjustments is reflected in the fact that the
dollops of molten glass (known as gobs) are squeezed out of a 70-ton tank at
1,000 degrees - and the temperature can be adjusted by two degrees at a
time. The plunger which presses each gob into a mould can be adjusted by
0.5mm. As plant manager Barrie Taylor says, 'output, yield and quality were
erratic'. Business applications were run remotely on a mainframe computer at
Philips' headquarters in the Netherlands.
The factory refit brought the opportunity to replace the hotchpotch of
systems with a single network developed from scratch. The Manman package
from ASK (recently taken over by Computer Associates) was chosen for
materials requirements planning (MRP).
An on-line information system was produced by IT specialist Steve Hewitt and
a colleague using the Powerhouse development language from Cognos.
The factory now has a small central Vax computer from Digital Equipment
which communicates with PCs on the factory floor and other devices which
monitor and count the screens as they progress from the mould to the
inspection area.
Another 70 PCs and terminals away from the factory floor give managers and
others access to the production information as well as to multi-user Vax
versions of Wordperfect and Lotus 1-2-3 for word processing and
spreadsheets.
A Cognos facility called Quick enables users to do detailed analysis, for
example to look at trends over longer periods.
Technical design was vital. 'We only have a small IT presence, so the system
had to be able to run round the clock without constant support,' Mr Hewitt
says.
'Communications handling was kept off the PCs and put in the central Vax. It
contacts each PC to collect data, typically every 10 seconds.' The Vax puts
the data in batches and updates the information system every few minutes.'
If the Vax goes out of action the factory PCs continue collecting data and
the managers' PCs hold production information up to the last update. If all
or part of the network goes down the computers affected continue working,
albeit in isolation.
In both cases, when links with the Vax are restored, the central machine
checks when it last received data and gathers the missing data from the
factory PCs. If a PC goes down the Vax notices after several attempts to
collect data and displays a message to the central computer operator.
There is further fall-back with the production counting systems. The
counters are at 25 points and connected to a PC; if the PC goes down the
counters have enough electronic memory to accumulate their totals until the
PC is back in action.
Mr Hewitt and a colleague developed the information system in Powerhouse in
three months. 'We were assured by other users in Philips that it was easy to
use and would enable us to do what we had planned, and that's how it turned
out,' he says. 'Even if we'd been able to find a packaged information system
it could have taken three months to implement it.'
Mr Taylor says yield and output have increased by 10 per cent since the
plant refit, and he believes most of that is down to the system. 'We now
have more sophisticated control and can intervene much earlier if there is a
problem,' Mr Taylor says. 'We therefore have lower statistical variations
and consistent output.'
Supplier profile Cognos: a Canadian company formed in 1969 and set up in the
UK in 1983.
Product: Powerhouse, a system development language. The latest version, 7.0,
was introduced in 1993. Sold direct and through 400 'Cognos partners'.
Turnover: latest turnover is CDollars 153m (Pounds 68.6m) and pre-tax profit
CDollars 2.3m (Pounds 1.03m). UK turnover is Pounds 12.9m and profit Pounds
1.1m.
Employees: 1,000 worldwide, including 100 in the UK.
Hardware and operating systems: Unix and proprietary machines from IBM
(AS/400 and RS/6000), Hewlett-Packard, ICL, Digital Equipment, Sun
Microsystems, Bull and Data General.
Number of users: Cognos has 12,000 customers worldwide, including 1,400 in
the UK.
Price: on application.
Sales and support/maintenance: annual maintenance is 15 per cent of the
licence charge.
Contact: UK head office.
Tel: 0344 486668.
Computer Associates
Product: Manman, consisting of 20 modules for managing manufacturing,
customer service, accounting and other business functions. The current
version, 9.4, was launched this year.
Supplier: Computer Associates took over ASK, developer of Manman, this year.
Employees: ASK, a US company, has 2,300 staff in 82 offices worldwide.
Computer Associates, formed in the US in 1978 and the UK in 1978, has 7,000
staff, including 400 in the UK.
Turnover: ASK had a Dollars 426m turnover last year. Computer Associates had
a turnover of more than Dollars 2.1bn.
Hardware and operating systems: Manman runs on Hewlett-Packard HP3000 and
HP900 and Digital Equipment Vax and Alpha computers.
Number of users: more than 3,000 worldwide.
Price: on application.
Contact: UK head office.
Tel: 0753 577733.
</TEXT>
