<DOCNO>FT944-5784</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ELAD8AHUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 94 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1994 (12): Upjohn links
up the orders - Moving to a global supply chain / A pharmaceuticals
manufacturer found a feeling of system ownership was created by introducing
a package designed to connect three separate systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pharmaceuticals manufacturer Upjohn is moving from three unconnected systems
in the UK to a worldwide supply chain in which demand for chemicals in one
country will automatically spark off orders in another.
The first step is the replacement of existing systems around the world by
the same BPCS package (Business Planning and Control System) from System
Software Associates (SSA), running on IBM AS/400 business computers.
The project is removing barriers between departments, improving negotiations
with customers and suppliers and changing attitudes towards computer
systems.
The US group has a UK factory in Crawley, Sussex, making 90 products, 60 per
cent of which are exported. UK turnover is Pounds 70m and there are about
500 staff.
The UK operation used to run manufacturing, purchasing and accounting on
separate IBM System/36 computers using a package installed 10 years before.
This meant information on customers and suppliers was keyed into different
systems.
The UK now has the single BPCS system, chosen by the US as the new group
standard.
'The company was very segmented,' says information systems manager Elizabeth
Bielby. 'The integrated system now forces functions to communicate and
operate as a single unit, because if data is entered in one area it affects
others.'
There is also better communication with the computing department. 'Things
have changed dramatically,' Mrs Bielby says. 'The old systems were very much
owned by the IT department and remote from the people who created and used
the data. Today the users own and drive the systems. Indeed we want to move
the entering data as close as possible to the people who create it. For
example, at present information from the shop floor is entered from paper
forms by supervisors; we want to have real-time data entry by the people
actually doing the production work.'
This feeling of system ownership was created not least by the way the system
was introduced. SSA trained 50 users, who used this standard training to
develop a course geared precisely to Upjohn's needs. These people then
trained their colleagues, mainly on the job as different functions came into
use.
Upjohn has modified the standard product to its own needs. SSA has built
some of these changes into new releases to ensure that Upjohn has a package
which is as near to the standard as possible. Upjohn currently has 10 major
modifications outside the standard product but Mrs Bielby says she hopes
this will fall to three with the next release, due for installation in
October.
'The package argument is that you buy into the supplier's development work,
and we're working hard to contain the number of modifications,' Mrs Bielby
says. 'But the downside to taking a package is that you get the same as
everyone else. We would continue to modify the package if we felt we would
gain significant competitive advantage.'
An unusual benefit of using a package in the chemicals industry relates to
regulation. Processes have to be formally inspected by regulatory bodies;
computer systems are part of those processes. 'SSA has done a lot of
validation work on the package, so the inspectors simply check the company's
own documentation,' Mrs Bielby says. 'This means we don't have to validate
our own systems. In fact, the costs can be so great that this alone means it
is no longer cost-effective to develop our own systems. So the validation
costs of the package are spread among all the customers, just as the
development costs are. This has emerged as a major benefit.'
The new system and new way of working have had a big effect. Output is up by
a third, with 7 per cent fewer staff. Inventory supplies of 3.5 months
comfortably beat the target of 4.3 months - and continue to fall by 6 per
cent a year. Better information, especially forecasts, means better
negotiations with customers and suppliers and a tighter linking of demand to
manufacturing.
This is being extended across the international group: Upjohn is now looking
at using information technology to bring all operations together so that
chemical plants are geared precisely to the needs of product manufacturing.
Supplier profile Product: BPCS (Business Planning and Control System),
described as an enterprise resource planning system supporting business
integration across research and development, manufacturing, sales, finance
and distribution.
Supplier: System Software Associates, a manufacturing systems specialist
formed in the US in 1981 and in the UK in 1987.
Turnover: turnover in 1993 was up 15 per cent at Dollars 263m; European
turnover was Dollars 101m. Net profit was Dollars 23.4m.
Hardware and operating systems: IBM AS/400; also being adapted for IBM and
Hewlett-Packard Unix computers.
Number of users: More than 7,000 worldwide.
Price: on application.
Contact: UK head office.
Tel: 0276 692111.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Upjohn.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
