<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 94 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1994 (8): Broad range of
entries
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of entries rose once again in the fourth year of the Business
Software Challenge '90s design competition for higher education students.
This time the judges were challenged even in deciding on a shortlist from
among such widely differing projects.
Sponsored and funded by Computer Associates, with Pounds 20,000 worth of
cash, hardware and software prizes, Business Software Challenge '90s is
supported by FT Software At Work, the British Computer Society, the
Institute of Management and Coopers and Lybrand.
The projects described (in no particular order) are taken from the shortlist
of eight that provided the eventual winners in two categories:
Overall Winner and
Best Business Solution.
Judges had to bear in mind the wide differences between the authors of the
submissions. These ranged from teams of HND students, (who had sometimes
produced a prototype system within a short deadline) to highly specialised
entries from individual postgraduate and PhD students.
The panel also used a broad definition of 'business solution', allowing any
well-defined problem well-researched, analysed and resolved to qualify, even
if it did not have widespread commercial potential.
Some had a broad 'horizontal application' for almost any business,
(Brainbox, Word-of-Mouth), whereas others were tightly-focused on a specific
business area, or even a specific user-company.
Nevertheless, as in 1993, the commercial potential of some of the systems
was obvious and a few of the entries produced professional documentation.
Some of them even presented some live implementations.
Information about the winners and next year's entries: contact the
Competition Secretary, Business Software Challenge '90s, PO Box 2ER, London
W1A 2ER; tel: 071 636 7366; fax: 071 636 7876.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
