<HEADLINE>
FT  01 DEC 94 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1994 (7): Inland Revenue
asks for a discount - On-line information / Claire Gooding looks at the way
the tax authorities are using their accounting system to negotiate discounts
with suppliers and keep tight budget control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A radical change of culture is taking place at the Inland Revenue, not least
because it is expected to spend money as efficiently as it collects it. Like
any other government department, the Revenue is taking responsibility for
its own procurement.
According to assistant director of procurement, John Cavell, it is leading
the way with its PCS - Purchasing Cycle System.
Walker's software had already been chosen as the basis of PCS when Mr
Cavell, whose responsibilities include contracts and purchasing, took over
his post three years ago. A believer in the principle that 'information is
power', his brief was to maximise the purchasing power of the Revenue, and
that included keeping track of how much had been committed to a particular
supplier.
'Experience has proved that you can make 80 per cent of savings without a
computer system just by using professional practices, but you can get the
extra 20 per cent by using a computer,' he says. 'The information it
supplies gives you the purchasing power to negotiate discounts.'
The Revenue wanted to record projects involving ongoing commitments as well
as upfront payments. Although a certain amount of tailoring was needed for
the Accounts Payable, Stock Control and Purchasing modules, Mr Cavell says:
'Where possible we've tried to stick to the standard package because we
recognise that the more we modify it, the more costly it becomes.' The
Revenue used outside consultants, including Ernst and Young, on the
contract.
Currently 700 sites are served by PCS, which is adopting the system as part
of project Iron, the Inland Revenue Office for the Nineties. For end users
the system runs on PCs, although the big advantage is the mainframe
centralisation of data. The commitment accounting (Encumbrance) module,
which the Revenue encouraged Walker to complete, is a particular attraction
for end users because they can make forward planning commitments as well as
tracking cash payments for goods and services that have already been
delivered.
'We trap expenditure at source so that we know up front how much is
committed in the long term,' explains Mr Cavell. 'It helps with delegated
budgets and what we term empowerment, where people are responsible for their
own budgets. Previously bills were paid centrally at Worthing, but now users
can have a halfway house, accessing the system from their own screen.'
The project, worth a total of Pounds 500,000 in current terms, is planned to
save more than Pounds 20m, achieved from early payment discounts, a
reduction in printed forms and stockholding.
Supplier profile Product: Release 16.5 of Walker's mainframe applications
include management budgeting and accounting with General Ledger, Accounts
Payable, and Credit and Accounts Receivable Management System, which
provides instant credit and collection information as well as exception
reporting. Other modules include Asset Management, Project Cost Management,
and Inventory Management. Walker is also developing Redwood, a client-server
suite, and the newly-acquired Open/1 software has been renamed Aptos
following the acquisition of its developer, UK-based mid-range accounts
software house FSL.
Suppliers: UK-based Walker International, is part of US-owned Walker
Interactive Systems which is headquartered in San Francisco with offices
worldwide.
Turnover: Dollars 65.11m in 1993, with Dollars 3.9m profit; Dollars 62.8m in
1992 with Dollars 7.9m profit.
Employees: 140 in the UK, 550 worldwide.
Number of users: 600 large sites worldwide.
Price: average order of Pounds 250,000: price depends on level of
integration and support.
Hardware and operating systems: mainframe and client-server platforms
including HP-UX, AIX, MVS, Sybase, Oracle, DB2, CICS, and Transarc's Encina.
Sales and support/maintenance: direct sales and support charges are
negotiable.
Other services available: training and consultancy.
User views: flexible design, tight integration between modules, open to
tailoring.
Contact: Caroline Borland at Walker International.
Tel: 0296 432951.
</TEXT>
